05822nam a22007335i 9783110751451DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021944786  a97831107514517 a10.1515/97831107514512doi  a(DE-B1597)583369  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aHIS0370602bisacsh00aMarriage Discourses :bHistorical and Literary Perspectives on Gender Inequality and Patriarchic Exploitation /ced. by Frank Jacob, Jowan A. Mohammed. 1aMünchen ;aWien : bDe Gruyter Oldenbourg, c[2021] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (V, 260 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- t1. Idealized Romantic Love, Legal Issues, and Patriarchic Exploitation: An Introduction to Historical and Literary Marriage Discourses -- tSection I: Marriage Discourses in Law and Politics -- t2. Political Marriage in Antiquity -- t3. Marriage Discourses in Conflict: Public and Private Order in Early Modern Spain -- t4. Challenging Patriarchy: Marriage and the Reform of Marriage Law in Imperial Germany and the Weimar Republic -- tSection II: Marriage Discourses and Social Criticism -- t5. On the Discourse of the "New Sexual Morality" in the German Empire: Robert Michels' Sexual Ethics between Women's Movement, Social Democracy, and Sociology -- t6. Marriage as Exploitation: Emma Goldman and the Anarchist Concept of Female Liberation -- t7 To End the Yoke of Marriage: Mary Hunter Austin and the Struggle Against Patriarchal Norms -- tSection III: Marriage Discourses in Literature -- t8. Redefining Marriage in Interwar Britain: Internal Transformation and Personal Sacrifice in the Poetry of H.D. -- t9. Scenes from a Marriage: The Age of Innocence as Discourse on the Transactional Value of Marriage -- t10. "Marriages are just performances": Staging Fashion, Comedy, and Feminism in Love, Loss and What I Wore -- tContributors -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aMarriage was historically not only a romantic ideal, but a tool of exploitation of women in many regards. Women were often considered commodities and marriage was far away from the romantic stereotypes people relate to it today. While marriages served as diplomatic tools or means of political legitimization in the past, the discourses about marital relationships changed and women expressed their demands more openly. Discourses about marriage in history and literature naturally became more and more heated, especially during the "long" 19th century, when marriages were contested by social reformers or political radicals, male and female alike. The present volume provides a discussion of the role of marriage and the discourses about in different chronological and geographical contexts and shows which arguments played an important role for the demand for more equality in martial relationships. It focuses on marriage discourses, may they have been legal or rather socio-political ones. In addition, the disputes about marriage in literary works of the 19th and 20th centuries are presented to complement the historical debates.  afunded by Nord University  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 4aDiskurs. 4aEhe. 4aGender. 4aGeschichte. 4aLiteratur. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aMarriage discourses.  agender roles.  amarital relations.  amarriage.1 aAllen Hanssen, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCallison, Jamie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFargas Peñarrocha, Mariela, 